KLLM Transport regarding an approximate 4-gallon hazmat that released on a trailer. The driver was unloading at a customer location when he noticed the release. The initial cause is currently unknown. No drain or waterways are reported to have been impacted by the release. ERTS will review conditions for regulatory reporting based on the contractor's assessment once they arrive on site.   KLLM reports that the material released is Alamine 304-1 from a poly tote (not sure if it's 275g or 330g). The driver has contained the released inside the trailer with his spill kit and moved to a concrete surface just outside of the Customer's property. The SDS for this product indicates that the material begins to solidify at 59 degrees Fahrenheit and the current ambient temperature at this location is 45 degrees. The contractor arrived on site at 1820 ET. the impacted area of the trailer measures approximately 3x5ft. The spill is approximately 3-gallons. The product was defrosted and transferred into drums for pending disposal. The impacted areas were cleaned and waste collected for disposal.

column168: UTLX 211782 was identified as releasing by the BNSF Railway Mechanical during an inbound inspection in the BNSF Railway Terminal in Stockton, CA on December 2, 2019.  The Train Crew personnel and Mechanical Department identified the release due to a strong odor of Ethanol when directly next to the car.  The cause of the release was identified by BNSF Mechanical HMERT Responder as loose man way swing bolts, as the car had zero pressure when attempting to relieve the internal pressure to inspect the man way.  Three of the eight man way swing bolts were identified as less than tool tight and required tightening to secure.  The man way seal (Seal # 74311) was removed for inspection of the man way gasket to ensure a gasket was present.  The gasket was present and in a serviceable condition.  The man way was then secured to allow movement with a replacement seal (Seal # 542209) applied.  I have attached the report received by the Mechanical GF II who responded and secured the release.

column42: BUTADIENES, STABILIZED OR BUTADIENES AND HYDROCARBON MIXTURE, STABILIZED CONTAINING MORE THAN 40% BUTADIENES
column168: On 12/06/2019 at around 2008 hours Central Standard Time, CSXT personnel and CSX Hazmat contractors reported a release from tank car SHPX221497, load Butadienes and Hydrocarbon Mixtures, Stabilized, coming from the top of the car at Gentilly Yard, New Orleans, LA. The car was isolated and the shipper, Westlake, was notified. SPSI, a CSXT response contractor, responded and found a release coming from the liquid line valve. SPSI observed visible icing around the plug of the liquid line valve and observed high readings of VOC on air monitoring equipment.  It was determined that the liquid line valve would not close any further and the plug was not installed properly.  Once the plug was installed properly the release was secured.  A field transfer is scheduled for a future date and the car will not continue in service until it is transferred onsite. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Westlake (Mr. Harris C: 270-703-9367; dharris@westlake.com).        NAR Cause Code: 300 – Liquid line valve; other  2(5+5+0) x (2+4) = 80 NARRI   New Orleans, LA 12/06/19 – SHPX221497, Butadienes Stabilized

column168: The shipment was discovered during the clearance process. The package appeared to have frost/ice on the exterior of the box. The inner contents were 2(4L) metal cans labelled Ethyl Acetate, wrapped in blue plastic film/bubble wrap,also in the box were 7 Printer heads(valued at $42K). No Markings or labels to indicate that the inner contents were dg. The shipper provided a SDS that confirms the UN# and PSN. The shipment has been placed in a salvage drum and held for FAA investigation.

These packages met tne requirements or IATA special provision Ab/ per the shipper and were offered as nonhazardous. However, the boxes used for the batteries were not strong enough for the gross package weight of the batteries and several of the packages broke open. Two packages were broken in the Memphis hub and repacked and sent on to the recipient. Twenty packages made it to the destination ramp but several of the boxes fell apart on the belt. Some of the protective caps came off at this time and the battery terminals came in contact with metal on the belt system. Some of the batteries exhibited spark and smoke but did not singe. They did not require the use of a fire extinguisher. I asked them to tape the terminals and place them in a salvage drum with cushioning and contact the recipient to see if they would pick up the shipment. They were unable to reach the recipient. The shipper was contacted. They requested that the batteries be returned to them. We will repackage the batteries in boxes after adding additional electrical tape to the terminals and plan to return them to the shipper as requested.

column168: Highway Transport driver was traveling east on I-40 (Knoxville,TN), when the vehicle in front of him suddenly changed lanes to avoid hitting an unoccupied/abandon vehicle in the travel lanes. Highway driver was not fortunate enough to avoid hitting the unoccupied/abandon vehicle. Driver struck the rear of the vehicle and lost control resulting in striking the concrete divider and laying the trailer over against the concrete barrier. The trailer was damaged but no product escaped the tank. The product was later transferred into another cargo tank  with no spills nor exposures.   Officers spoke with witness, Andre Dukes, who stated he was driving on I-40 East prior to the accident. Dukes stated he saw Vehicle-2 in the middle lane with no lights or flashers on. Next to the vehicle was a white female who flagged down Dukes. The unknown female stated she had run out of gas and needed to get a ride to the vehicles owner. Dukes stated the woman wanted a ride to the Royal Inn at 1914 Ailor Avenue. Dukes transported the woman and dropped her off at an intersection near Middlebrook and Citco. Dukes stated the woman got out and walked toward the Royal Inn. Dukes described the female as white with blondish hair, approximately35-45 years old, approximately 5'2"- 5'4" in height wearing a dark blue or black top and grey pants with white shoes. Dukes stated the female was thin and appeared nervous or scared.

While loading drums onto a trailer at the Veolia ten day intransit facility, a Veolia employee noticed  liquid running down the trailer.  At first, due to the weather, the Veolia employee thought the liquid was rainwater but upon further investigation the liquid was observed to be leaking from the 55 gallon drum. The drum was then identified as being punctured at the top rim resulting in approximately 1 liquid gallon of waste flammable liquid to be leaked from the container.  The leaking drum was  overpacked and the spill was cleaned up by a Veolia employee.
column169: Upon investigation the drum did not appear to be in a condition suitable to transport liquid material  without leaking.  To prevent this from occurring again in the future, Veolia will provide training to  remind the Veolia operations employees to verify that the containers are properly rated for the type of material they were filled with and also to ensure that containers are of good integrity and in  proper condition for safe transport.

The trailer was top loaded in Pottstown PA. The driver departed the transfer site and after driving for 15 minutes (approximately 10 miles) he was advised by other drivers that the product was coming out of the top of the trailer. When our driver pulled over he climbed the ladder and discovered that a washout cap on the dome was missing. Due to missing washout cap, product splashed on two vehicles and drivers stated they had headaches.     The root cause of this incident is that EPS Williamsport MD removed the washout cap on 12/12/19 when this unit delivered there for vapor recovery. The washout cap was not replaced correctly and although the washout cap felt tight when hand pressure was applied, it was not securely fastened.  (Possibly Cross Threaded)
column169: Highway Transport has developed a "Top load inspection procedure”. This procedure will list inspections and actions to be performed by a driver/mechanic when a trailer has been designated for top loading.   Future performance can be measured by Highway Transport of top load inspection documents and a zero recurrence of spills on top loaded trailers.

On 12/6/19 at approximately 14:12, the UTLX 649297 was found by yard personnel to be leaking a small amount of oil from the top of the car near the manway. The car was isolated and trained hazmat responders reported to the yard to the inspect the car.  Upon arrival, the responders immediately found that all manway securement bolts were less than tool tight causing oil to leak from the sealing area when the car was moved.  Responders opened the manway cover, inspected the gasket and cleaned the surface.  The manway was properly secured and the car was cleaned and put back into transportation.  NRC Environmental performed cleanup and demobilized.

column168: On 12/2/19, the UTLX 203069 was found leaking a small amount of liquid from the fittings cover while in the Denver yard.  Crews isolated the car and BNSF Hazmat responders inspected the car.  It was found that the fittings plate bolts were all loose by approximately 1/4 turn.  The car was placed on a RIP track for secondary inspection and pressure testing by contractor personnel.  Contractors arrived and found a slight leak from underneath the liquid valve.  This valve was found to not be tool tight on the welded nipple. The air valve was also not tool tight.  All fittings were inspected and the car was monitored with 10 psi of pressure to inspect for leaks using soap and water.  No additional leaks were found.  Suncor was notified to obtain an OTMA to move the car back to origination (Commerce City) for handling and bubble leak testing.  All spill gasoline evaporated from the car and no cleanup was necessary.
column169: Suncor to follow up with UTLX shop in Eldorado, KS for RCA.  The car was just inspected at shop.(NAR:282)

column168: On 12/5/19, the LYBX 4030 was found with a slow drip from the bottom of the car during outbound inspection while in the train at Barstow, CA. The area was isolated and BNSF Hazmat Responders arrived to inspect the car and leak.  It was identified that a slow drip was originating from the bottom outlet flange area. Two bolts were identified as loose on the flange connecting the valve to the tank car.  Responders tightened the bolts and the leak immediately stopped.  The car was released and held at Corona, CA pending shipper recieving an OTMA for further movement and to consignee and for bubble leak testing.  Lyondell is working on the OTMA and shopping.
column169: Shipper should review maintenance records and procedures for ensuring flange bolts are tight and leak free.(NAR:535)

column168: An odor next to his car was reported by a switching crew with one of the crew members requesting to go to the hospital for evaluation shortly thereafter.  Upon arrival an odor was present at ground level next to the car.  The car was climbed and frosting was visible on the exterior of the B end protective housing.  The seal was removed, the cover opened, and a visible leak was emitting from the B end liquid valve in a spray like fashion from the plug. The valve was checked and found to be open approximately 1/8 of a turn and the plug was less than tool tight. The leak slowed when the valve was closed.  The plug was properly secured and the remaining valves and fittings were checked with no issues found.  The car was resealed and released back into transportation.
column169: Ensure the car is properly secured prior to releasing into transportation

column168: On December 9, 2019, at approximately 3:54 AM CST, a pallet containing twelve (12) 1-gallon pales of paint tipped over in transit. As a result, approximately eighty (80) pounds of paint released to the R+L Carriers (RLC) trailer interior. Following the release, the RLC unit parked at the above-referenced location for assessment and offload. At approximately 4:05 AM CST, a representative from RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (DES) to manage the environmental remediation of the site on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HE) to assess and remediate the site as necessary. At approximately 6:20 AM CST, a crew from HE arrived on-site. Following a site assessment, HE personnel observed approximately eighty (80) pounds released to the trailer interior. HE deployed granular absorbents to the paint impacted trailer interior, and absorbent pads to the paint impacted pallets. All spent absorbents, damaged pails, and debris were collected and containerized into one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. HE secured the site and demobilized, noting no further actions required.

column168: HOLSTON GASES PROPANE BOBTAIL WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON ALLENVILLE ROAD AT APPROXIMATELY 40 MPH WHEN THE DRIVER ENCOUNTERED A TRACTOR TRAILER TRAVELING WESTBOUND AT THE TOP OF A SMALL RISE. DRIVER STATED THAT HE MOVED AS FAR AS HE COULD TO THE SOUTH EDGE OF THE PAVEMENT TO AVOID THE OTHER TRUCK. RIGHT SIDE TIRES DROPPED OFF THE EDGE OF THE ASPHALT. DRIVER STATED HE TRIED TO LET THE TRUCK SLOW BUT WHEN HE ATTEMPTED TO BRING THE TRUCK BACK ONTO THE ROADWAY THE LOAD (PROPANE LIQUID) SHIFTED AND CAUSED THE TRUCK TO OVERTURN. TRUCK CAME TO REST OFF THE ROADWAY ON THE BORTH SIDE OF THE ROAD. DRIVER SUSTAINED MINOR INJURIES (CUTS AND BRUISES) AND WAS EVENTUALLY TRANSPORTED TO HOSPITAL AS A PRECAUTION AND TO HAVE CUTS TO HIS HEAD TREATED. IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING THE ACCIDENT THE DRIVER STATED THAT THE CAB HAD FILLED WITH PROPANE VAPOR AND HE TURNED OFF THE IGNITION BEFORE EXITING THE CAB OF THE VEHICLE. THE TANK ON THE TRUCK WAS VENTING PROPANE FORM THE VAPOR VALVE AT THAT POINT. DRIVER ACTUATED THE EMERGENCY SHUT-OFF SYSTEM ON THE TRUCK/TANK WHICH SHUT OFF THE INTERNAL VALVES ON THE TANK. ONCE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL HAD ARRIVED AT THE SCENE (TODD COUNTY EMA) THEY SECURED THE SITE AND EVACUATED ON RESIDENT THAT LIVED IN CLOSE PROXIMITY THE ACCIDENT. NO OTHER RESIDENT WERE HOME DURING THE TIME. DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED TO HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT. ONCE ADDITIONAL HOLSTON GASES PERSONNEL ARRIVED AT THE SITE THE TANK PLUG WAS REMOVED FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK TO EXPEDITE THE VENTING OF THE PROPANE VAPOR BECAUSE ALL PERSONNEL INVOLVED DID NOT WANT TO ATTEMPT TO UPRIGHT THE VEHICLE UNTIL THE PROPANE TANK  HHAD STOPPED VENTING PROPANE VAPOR FOR SAFETY REASONS. ONCE THE PROPANE VAPOR HAD STOPPED VENTING THE PLUG WAS REPLACED AND THE VEHICLE WAS UPRIGHTED AND TOWED TO A LOCAL TOWING COMPANY (3 DOGS TOWING) LOCATED AT 980 ALFRED THUN ROAD IN CLARKSVILLE, TN. ONCE TRUCK WAS UPRIGHT HOLSTON PERSONNEL OBSERVED THAT THE LIQUID LEVEL GAUGE ON THE TANK WAS READING 17%. DRIVER INDICATED 28-30% WAS ON THE TRUCK AT THE TIME  OF THE ACCIDENT. APPROXIMATELY 400 GAL HAD BEEN RELEASED BASED ON THESE READINGS.
column169: THIS PARTICULAR INCIDENT HAPPENED ON A NARROW RURAL ROAD. THE EASTBOUND LANE THAT THE HOLSTON GASES TRUCK WAS DRIVING IN WAS DETERMINED TO BE 8 1/2 FT WIDE AND AND WESTBOUND LANE THAT OTHER VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING IN WAS APPROX. 10 FT IN WIDE. BASED ON DISCUSSIONS WITH THE HOLSTON GASES DRIVER IT APPEARS AS THOUGH BOTH DRIVERS ATTEMPTED TO TAKE ACTIONS TO AVOID A POTENTIAL HEAD-ON COLLISION BY MOVING AS FAR AS THEY COULD TO THE EDGE OF THE ROADWAY HOWEVER, THE HOLSTON GASES DRIVER GOT TOO CLOSE TO THE EDGE AND DROPPED OFF THE EDGE OF THE PAVEMENT. HOLSTON GASES HAS INSTRUCTED OUR DRIVERS IN THE PAST TO STOP IF AT ALL POSSIBLE WHEN THEY CONFRONT ANOTHER TRUCK ON NARROW ROADS BUT IN THIS INSTANCE THERE WAS INSUFFICIENT TIME TO DO SO.  AS A FOLLOW-UP SINCE THE ACCIDENT, THE LOCAL OR STATE ROAD DEPARTMENT HAD ADDED ADDITIONAL BLACKTOP ALONG THE EDGE OF THE EASTBOUND LANE WHERE THIS INCIDENT/ACCIDENT OCCURRED. TO MINIMIZE THE DROPOFF AND ADD ADDITIONAL WIDTH TO THE LANE.

column168: On December 17,2019, at approximately 11:05 AM CST, a forklift punctured one(1) 55-gallon drum containing black paint at the above-referenced R&L Carriers (RLC) location. As a result of the puncture, approximately fifty(50) pounds of black paint released to the concrete surface and trailer interior. At approximately 11:16 AM CST, a representative from RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES) to manage the environmental remediation of the site on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from NRC Environmental Services (NRC) to assess and remediate the site on their behalf. At approximately 1:10 PM CST, a crew from NRC arrived on-site. Following a site assessment, NRC observed approximately fifty (50) pounds of black paint released to the concrete surface and trailer interior. NRC deployed granular absorbents to the impacted surfaces and utilized hand tools to collect and containerize all spent absorbents into one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. NRC then deployed Simple Green cleaning solution to the concrete surface and trailer interior to remove any residual product and staining. NRC utilized absorbent pads to collect and containerize all spent cleaning solution into the drum. The damaged 55-gallon drum was then overpacked into one(1) 85-gallon drum for transport and disposal. NRC secured the site and demobilized, noting no further actions required

column168: Austin Powder Company (USDOT 103999) Truck/tanker combination was making a delivery to their own facility at 332 Ekonk Hill Rd, Moosup CT on the morning of December 2, 2019.  The driver was unloading Ammonium nitrate emulsion (UN3375) from a DOT 407 tanker trailer into a bulk bin.  The driver was away from the controls while doing this- driver claimed to be on the opposite side of the vehicle.  Being in said position is not in compliance with Austin Powder Company policy.  The 100 PSI burst disk on the tanker blew, and caused roughly 3,000 lbs of the material to spray out and be released onto the ground.  The spill was contained to a large gravel pad, and no drains or waterways were impacted.  Austin arranged for an outside contractor to clean the material up.  A vacuum truck sucked up the material and placed in in 12 drums.  Much of the material was returned to inventory for use.  The remainder that could not be used (2 drums of contaminated material) was taken to a disposal facility, where it is currently being profiled.  Once the test results are in, the material will be disposed of according to the profiling.
column169: Our policy is for drivers to be at the controls during the unloading process.  While it seldom occurs, burst disks rupture and having the driver present at the controls mitigates the potential amount released.  This driver was violating company policy. He was given a suspension for the misconduct.  The policy will be reemphasized with the rest of our driver group working out of this facility.

column168: On December 16, 2019, an FRA HazMat inspector reported that SCMX 6511, a tank car loaded of Styrene Monomer, Stabilized, was leaking product from the bottom of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Shell Chemical, was notified.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car was leaking product from the bottom outlet valve.  HEPACO contained the release by application of a Hazmat Hammock.  The car was then moved into CSX’s adjacent yard tracks to an area it could be isolated in an effort to reduce any risk to the safety of the public or CSX employees.  HEPACO continued to monitor the car until such time that Joe McCann, CSX Sr. Manager of Hazardous Materials, mobilized to the site.  Upon Mr. McCann’s arrival it was determined that the release was persisting due to a faulty bottom outlet valve and a secondary closure cap with a worn gasket.  Mr. McCann, and HEPACO personnel, removed the secondary closure cap and installed a new gasket into the closure cap- this stopped the release of product from the car.  Subsequently, Shell personnel, and HEPACO, transloaded the contents of the car into a non-defective tank car so the contents could be forwarded on; the SCMX 6511 was moved to shop for repair via OTMA.

column168: Norfolk Southern personnel reported an odor around tank car GLNX86268.  Upon inspection by a contractor, the source of the odor was a vapor leak coming from the vapor line valve. BNSF Car Inspectors observed product leaking down the side of the UTLX 664749.  Further inspection found that the valves and valve plugs were loose and had little to no sealant tape.  Sealant tape was applied to the valves and valve plugs, and everything was tightened tool tight.

column168: On December 10, 2019, at approximately 5:40 am CST, R+L Carrier personnel at the above referenced location observed a damaged 50 pound bag of UN1479(Sodium Persulfate) on a pallet located at dock door 18. As a result of the damage, an unknown amount of sodium persulfate was released to the remaining cargo within the pallet. At approximately 5:58 am CST, a representative with R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC.(CES) to manage the environmental remediation of the site on their behalf. Based of the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from Enviro Products and Services of Vermont(EPV) to assess and remediate the site as necessary. At approximately 8:30 am CST, a crew from EPV arrived on- site. Following a site assessment, crews noted sodium persulfate that was released from an unknown bag within the pallet of cargo. The release was contained within the plastic wrap and nothing had released to the concrete surface. Crews removed the plastic and observed two damaged bags of sodium persulfate. Crews removed the damaged bags and utlized hand tools to sweep the remaining powder. All sodium persulfate impacted material was collected and containerized in one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. EPV personnel noted no further actions were required on-site and crews demobilized

At approximately 7:00 p.m. CST, a representative with R+L retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C.(CES) to manage the environmental cleanup of the site. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager  dispatched a crew from Hazmat Special Services(HSS) to assess and remediate the site. Crews 1 removed cargo from the trailer as need to gain access to the spill. HSS deployed granular absorbents to the impacted areas to recover as much paint as possible. All spent absorbents and impacted debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 55 gallon poly drum for transport and disposal. Once the cleanup was approved by terminal personnel, HSS moved on to cleanup a separate spill at door 9 of the terminal.On December 30,2019 HSS arrived and assessed the site. column168: This shipment was called in as hazmat, but the driver was not given the required hazmat paperwork or placards when he originally departed from the shipper. The driver asked the shipper about hazmat paperwork and he was advised at their location that it wasn’t needed which he took to mean the freight was non-hazardous. The shipper loaded, secured and sealed the shipment so the driver was unable to view the freight and see the markings/labels on the freight prior to departure. The driver sent a message to dispatch that he departed. Dispatch contacted the shipper/calling party contact via cell phone to verify we had the correct freight since we were expecting hazmat, at which time the customer advised it should have been hazmat. Dispatch asked the driver to stop in the next safe location and permission was given by the customer to break to seal to verify. Driver discovered hazmat required markings and labels on the freight. The shipper left the facility immediately after our driver departed so they were unable to provide paperwork until they reopened in the morning. Driver was 17 miles from the shipper, but not at a location he could park overnight. The nearest FedEx facility with parking was 32 miles and nearest truck stop with parking confirmed was 26 miles away. The customer gave permission for the driver to return and park at their location overnight, so we selected that option since it was the shortest transit. The driver was given correct hazmat paperwork and placards before departing their location on 12/19/2019.
column169: FDCC: reviewed procedure with the driver that requires a phone call any time the freight received does not match the description given. Message also sent to the fleet as a hazmat process reminder.  Shipper: Loading staff's training program should allow them to identify the need for a shipper's declaration of dangerous goods when the freight bears markings and labels.

column17: North East Freightways dba Land Air Express
column168: Packages were upright, stainless steel, drums, with fittings on top that were protected by metal shroud. Fittings were of both a threaed and a "secured by band clamp," similiar to that on the top of a drum, but of approximately 3" diameter. Outage space was pressurized to 5psi with nitrogen. Ultimate failure on 5 of 8 packages was a loosening of a single screw holding each band clamp, causing the internal pressure to force material out as it sloshed within container during transit.  Employees and driver noted faint "residual" smell of material at time of loading and departure. None noted concerning smell or visible release of material.  Driver noted that smell increased as he worked through the morning, though it did not reach an alarming level.  Approximately 5 hours and multiple stops from departure, shipment arrived at consignee. Smell was then noted as "strong" and consignee did further inspection of packages. It was then found that material was run from top of packages and leached between package and encapsulating stretchwrap. Only 1 of 5 packages released enough material to stain approximately 12" diameter spot on floor. No trace of material was found on underside of wooden trailer floor, with no release outside of trailer.  Chemtrec was contacted, report # 2019121200246. They decided no immediate response was needed. trailer was staged in secured area in consignee yard. Tedia flew in specialists on 12/16. They discovered loosened band clamps and corrected the defect.  Clean Harbors Arrived on 12/19 and decontaminated trailer. Consignee refused shipment and freight was moved back to shipper in OH.
column169: Land Air will no longer allow transport of this type packaging from this shipper due to what was described by them as a "known issue" with this type of packaging.

column168: At 1600 hours local time on Friday, December 13, 2019 a material handler was unloading drums from a trailer and staging them for shipment. One poly open-head 55-gallon drum slipped off the edge of a pallet and fell, popping off its lid on impact with the concrete floor of the warehouse. The entire 50 gallons of liquid waste in the drum discharged onto the warehouse floor instantaneously. The material spread through the immediate area of the warehouse and some flowed under the warehouse door onto the dock area and parking lot. There was a light rain falling at the time and since the waste was mostly water it was impossible to determine exactly how far the spill itself migrated from the dock. The spilled material was identified as paint shop rinse-water from Kaman Aerospace in Bloomfield, CT, and consisted of water with some chromium content. DOT Class 9. RCRA hazardous waste D007. Spill pads and granular absorbents were used to contain and clean up the material in the warehouse. Drain covers
column169: Additional training for material handlers in safe movement of palatalized drums and containers. Liquid wastes to be accepted only in closed head drums going forward.

column168: No equipment or package failure. On 12/21/2019, 16:30 delivery driver committed an error in securing the elbow coupling to the customer's delivery tube nipple. Upon discovery of spillage, driver stopped flow by closing belly valve on trailer compartment, then notified company management and customer personnel. Spill duration was less than 2 minutes. County EMS responded to site for containment, and calculated product loss of 317 gallons ULSD. No surface water contact by the spilled product. Spill contained in drainage structure/piping (approx. 100') with some run-out in a dry storm ditch. No rain in immediate forecast. Carrier rep called ERC to report event in route to site. Carrier rep called for third party clean-up response. Carrier rep arrived on-site and confirmed EMS findings. Met with third party rep for clean-up strategy. Confirmed no rain in forecast and resumed/completed clean-up process on 12/22. Vac truck deployed for removal of impacted soil and collect run-off water from spill area pressure washing, plus wash-out of drainage structure/piping.
column169: Reiteration with driver(s) and driver trainers of the importance focus on each step of product and equipment handling - both loading and unloading. Standard procedures are in place to prevent this type of error. Field safety observations will continue to include this item for performance review.

column168: Driver noticed smoke emanating from rear of tanker vehicle and immediately exited highway and parked on shoulder of exit ramp to investigate. Upon exiting vehicle, driver observed rear inner tire of tanker vehicle was on fire and the fire was too large to extinguish with vehicle fire extinguisher. Driver immediately contacted fire response agency by calling 911. Fire Department responded and extinguished fire. Heat from the fire impinged on bottom tank flange and damaging corresponding gasket. Damaged gasket resulted in a small but consistent leak from bottom flange outlet.  Driver placed absorbent pillows to contain the spilled sodium hypochlorite(bleach)and prevent entry into highway drainage ditch. CaITrans was onsite and provided additional dirt to erect a larger containment pond to prevent sodium hypochlorite from entering drainage ditch.  With the coordination of the local Fire Department Hazmat team and the California Highway Patrol, Hasa personnel arrived on scene and immediately began the transfer of remaining liquid from damaged tanker to another empty tanker. As tanker was being emptied, a hazardous waste response contractor, National Response Corporation (NRC), utilized a pump truck to recover the spilled bleach contained in the small containment pond erected to mitigate further spread of the spilled material. NRC utilized water to spray down area of containment pond to ensure that all residual bleach was recovered and area was cleaned. All wash water was pumped with spilled material into Intermediate Bulk Containers for further disposal. Duration of release was approximately 5.5 hours with approximately 900 gallons spilled and recovered with the use of pump vehicle.
column169: Provided refresher training to all drivers to ensure proper daily vehicle inspections of all equipment is being accomplished properly, specifically focused on brake and tire related system components.  Conducted a fleet wide inspection of all other tanker fleet equipment to ensure no other equipment was subject to similar incident

column168: ON 12/6/2019 EMPLOYEES OF CO-ALLIANCE LLP AT REYNOLDS, IN WERE ATTEMPTING TO CHANGE THE LIQUID VALVE ACME FITTING ON A 1500 GALLON ANHYDROUS AMMONIA PORTABLE TANK - CONTAINER W55.  USING CORDLESS IMPACT AND LARGE SOCKET WRENCH THEY BEGAN TO LOOSEN THE FITTING. IT APPEARS AS THE IMPACT WRENCH WAS WAS ACTIVATED, THE VIBRATION CAUSED VALVE TO OPEN SLIGHTLY, CAUSING THE WORKERS TO LEAVE THE AREA IMMEDIATELY THINKING THAT THE VALVE HAD BROKE. EMERGENCY ACTIONS/MEASURES WERE IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED.  THE FACILITY IS LOCATED ON THE NORTH SIDE OF TOWN AND THE WIND WAS BLOWING TOWARDS TOWN AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT. EMERGENCY MEASURES INCLUDED COVERING VALVE WITH WET CLOTH MATERIAL TO SUPPRESS THE VAPORS, CONSTRUCTING A BERM AROUND THE TANK TO COLLECT WATER AND ANY PRODUCT THAT DID NOT DISSIPATE INTO THE ATMOSPHERE, THE USE OF WATER SPRAY TO KEEP VAPOR TO A MINIMUM AND DEPRESSURIZING TANK W55 INTO A TANK OF WATER TANK. IDEM, NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, LEPC AND 911 WERE PROMPTLY NOTIFIED.  THE RESIDENTS FORM THE NEAREST HOME CAME TO OUR OFFICE TO INQUIRE ABOUT THE EMERGENCY ACTIVITIES. CO-ALLIANCE EMPLOYEES INFORMED THEM OF THE SITUATION. AS A PRECAUTION, WE ADVISED THEM TO LEAVE THE AREA FOR A COUPLE OF HOURS. FIRE DEPT. OFFICIALS MONITORED THE AREA FOR HEALTH AND SAFETY ISSUES. THE TANK WAS DEPRESSURIZED AND MOVED TO A SAFER, LESS POPULATED PART OF OUR FACILITY.  ON 12-7-2019 A CONTRACTOR EXCAVATED THE AREA WHERE THE TANK WAS SITTING. THE AFFECTED STONE AND SOIL WAS REMOVED SPREAD ON A NEARBY FARM.
column169: EMPLOYEE SAFETY TRAINING -SOP'S ASSOCIATED WITH MAINTENANCE. IMPACT WRENCH USE WILL BE PROHIBITED ON ALL TANK FITTINGS. -PROCEDURES FOR MAINTENANCE ACTIVITIES ON FULL TANKS.

column168: Univar Solutions driver was unloading bulk Caustic Soda 30% into the customers storage tank when he heard what sounded like rain as a result of product coming from the top of the tank, spraying all over.  Approx 1.5 inches of product was in containment with approximately 30 gallons of product was outside on the concrete and parking area.  During the unloading process, customer employees monitor the tank level from the control room due to no local level display being available at the storage tank. During the filling process the customer employee left the control room and during the time he was away, the overfill occurred.  Due to the chemical line of fire, our employee was unable to immediately reach the tank shut off values.  He made the decision to reach into the line of fire and turn off the shut off valve on his truck.  He immediately went to an emergency shower and washed off.  He then called the BOM to report the incident.  BOM said he needed to go wash at least a second time.  Our employee did finally reach the customer employees to report the spill and they initiated the clean up. Per the driver the clean up was in progress and nothing had left the property while he was onsite.   383 POUNDS released.    Site management at SPF worked to clean up the release when it happened.  The Univar Solutions driver was told to leave.  Univar Solutions management continued to follow up and assist with waste disposal from cleanup.
column169: Univar Solutions root cause analysis recommends that we reach out to SPF and determine if we can ensure their employee remains on site and with our employee during off loading of our tanker trucks.  We need to ensure that there is someone in the control room to evaluate the tank levels so that this does not happen again.

column168: The cause of damage is reportedly due to package fail.

Driver arrived at consignee and connections were made to the trailer and consignee valve while wearing proper PPE (chemical suit, chemical gloves, hard-hat w/ face-shield and goggles) . The unloading process utilized plant air at approximately 20 PSI. After product began flowing, driver noticed that there was product dripping from the QRB external valve clamp. The driver intended to tighten the QRB clamp to stop the drip while the product was still unloading and under pressure, but, loosened the QRB clamp instead.  When he did so, the clamp "blew off" causing the QRB manifold and clamp to separate from the QRB housing hitting the driver in his right hip which caused a small amount of caustic to splash under his face-shield getting some caustic on his lips. Driver was treated at the customers site for the burn on his lips then sent to an Urgent Care facility for evaluation/treatment. Driver was later released from Urgent Care with ointment (lip-balm) to condition/treat his lips. No injury was reported nor treatment provided to driver's right hip.

column168: On December 23, 2019, at 1030 hours, Mechanical Inspector at the Conrail Port Reading Yard, Port Reading,  New Jersey reported to the Trainmaster  that NTLX 1025, a residue tank car of UN1230, Methanol Solutions  was leaking from the bottom of the tank car. Reportedly, the product was coming from the bottom outlet valve.  The Consignee, Kinder Morgan Bulk Terminals, was notified directly to inform them of the situation and to provide  Conrail a responsible party at Twinco Romax. Hepaco, a Conrail emergency response contractor and Hazardous  Material Manager Joe Caccamo, were dispatched to the Port Reading Yard. After further inspection it was found that the leak was caused by a partially open bottom outlet valve handle. The toggle on the bottom outlet pin was in the straight position which allowed it to come out and the valve was able to partially open. The toggle on the  bottom outlet pin was lubricated and placed back after the valve was placed in the closed position. Additionally, it was found that bottom outlet valve cap and bonnet were less than tool tight, the vapor valve was partially open and both the vapor and liquid line secondary securement plugs were less than tool tight. All items were properly  secured. The tank car also had a broken weld on the safety handrail on the left side of the tank car that Conrail Mechanical forces repaired prior to placing the tank car back into transportation.  NARRI: 5x(4+3+0)x(2+0) = 70 Cause code:148

column168: Driver was using air pressure to unload.  At the end of the offload 100 gallons came out of the top of the customer tank.  The initial report was that it was the last surge of air that came through the lines.  After further review the driver felt the air start to go through the lines and he shut down right away.  As he was closing the internal valve he noticed product coming out from inside the building meaning it was happening prior to the hose going empty.  Based on the math prior to delivery there should have been 300 gallons of extra headspace in the customer tank and driver was using minimal air pressure (15psi).  There customer wasn't assisting in the offload or it could've been minimized.  We also train our drivers to shut down when they are nearing the end of the offload and then just crack the external valve open to minimize the effects of transitioning from liquid to air in the lines.  Driver had stated that the tank was no see through but we later learned it is semi-transparent, the lighting was fine at the time, and there is markings on the tank.  We also believe this to be an overflow issue, not the last surge of air.
column169: We submitted a request for the customer to verify their tank calibrations to avoid a future repeat.  Our driver has been brought in for performance training to ensure he understands the correct processes.

(HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, PHOSPHORIC ACID) TIPPED OVER DURING TRANSPORT AND RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS FROM THE BUNG TO THE TRAILER, ASPHALT, AND ADJACENT SOIL.  THE DRIVER DEPLOYED ABSORBENT PADS TO THE RELEASE UNDER THE TRAILER FOR CONTAINMENT. AT APPROXIMATELY 6:50 P.M. CST, A REPRESENTATIVE WITH FC RETAINED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES, L.C. (CES) TO MANAGE THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP OF THE SITE. BASED ON THE AVAILABLE INFORMATION, THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER DISPATCHED A CREW FROM ALPHA-OMEGA TRAINING AND COMPLIANCE (AOTC) TO ASSESS AND REMEDIATE THE SITE. AT APPROXIMATELY 9:23 P.M. CST, AOTC PERSONNEL ARRIVED AND ASSESSED THE SITE. CREWS BROKE THE TRAILER SEAL AND OPENED THE RIGHT TRAILER DOOR. AOTC OBSERVED A LEAKING 55-GALLON POLY DRUM AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WHICH WAS STACKED ON A PALLET ON TOP OF A 275-GALLON TOTE. THE 55-GALLON DRUM HAD TIPPED OVER DURING TRANSPORT AND WAS PINNED AGAINST THE LEFT TRAILER DOOR. AOTC SECURED THE POLY DRUM TO THE TRAILER WALL WITH STRAPS AND SUPPORTED FROM THE UNDERSIDE TO ALLOW THE LEFT TRAILER DOOR TO BE OPENED. ONCE THE DOOR WAS OPENED, CREWS HAD ACCESS TO THE DRUMS BUNG AND PERFORMED A TRANSFER TO ANOTHER DRUM. AOTC UTILIZED ABOSRBENT PADS AND GRANULAR ABSORBENTS TO RECOVER SPILLED PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER AND ASPHALT. ALL SPENT ABSORBENTS, PPE, AND CLEANUP DEBRIS WERE COLLECTED AND CONTAINERIZED INTO ONE (1) 55-GALLON DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. THE IMPACTED SOIL/ASPHALT MILLINGS ADJACENT TO THE ROADWAY WAS MARKED OFF WITH CONES FOR LATER EXCAVATION. THE CARGO WAS REPACKAGED AND SECURED IN THE TRAILER FOR TRANSPORT SO THE TRUCK AND TRAILER COULD LEAVE THE SCENE. AOTC DEMOBILIZED AND SCHEDULED TO RETURN AT A LATER DATE TO COMPLETE IMPACTED SOIL REMOVAL.

AS A RESULT OF THE DAMAGE, APPROXIMATELY ONE POUND OF UN3262 WAS RELEASED TO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  ON DECEMBER 11, 2019, AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00 A.M. CST, A REPRESENTATIVE FROM R+L CARRIERS RETAINED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES, L.C. (CES) TO MANAGE THE ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION OF THE SITE ON THEIR BEHALF. BASED ON THE AVAILABLE INFORMATION, THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER DISPATCHED A CREW FROM KARY ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (KES) TO ASSESS AND REMEDIATE THE SITE AS NECESSARY.
column169: ON DECEMBER 11, 2019, AT APPROXIMATELY 1:15 P.M. CST, A CREW FROM KARY ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (KES) ARRIVED ON-SITE. FOLLOWING A SITE ASSESSMENT, KES PERSONNEL NOTED APPROXIMATELY TWENTY-FIVE (25) POUNDS OF BLACK MAGIC INFUSION POWDER (CORROSIVE) WHICH COVERED APPROXIMATELY 6" X 15" RELEASED TO THE TRAILER FLOOR. KES PERSONNEL DEPLOYED 1 X 95-GAL POLY OVERPACK DRUM, 1 X 30-GAL POLY DRUM, 1 X 14-GAL POLY DRUM, AND ABSORBENT RAGS. ALL BLACK MAGIC INFUSION POWDER (CORROSIVE) IMPACTED MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED AND CONTAINERIZED IN 1 X 95-GAL POLY OVERPACK DRUM, 1 X 30-GAL POLY DRUM, AND 1 X 14-GAL DRUM FOR TRANSPORT AND DISPOSAL.  FOLLOWING THE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS, NO VISUAL OR OLFACTORY EVIDENCE OF THE CORROSIVE SOLID COULD BE OBSERVED AT THE SITE. BASED ON THESE RESULTS, IT APPEARS THAT THE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS WERE SUCCESSFUL, AND NO FURTHER ACTION SHOULD BE REQUIRED. CES RECOMMENDS THIS INCIDENT BE CLOSED.

column168: ERNEST CHAINEY LEFT SIDNEY MT HEADING NORTH ON HWY 200 FOR ALAMO NORTH DAKOTA, 86 MILES, TO LOAD OIL. HE THEN PROCEEDED EAST ON HWY 50 TO INTERSECTION OF HWY 42 TURNING SOUTH TO EPPING NORTH DAKOTA TO OFFLOAD. (27 MILES) APPROACHING INTERSECTION OF 42 & COUNTY RD 60TH ST NW THERE IS A STOP SIGN. ERNEST WAS SLOWED DOWN TO 35 MPH WHEN HE APPLIED THE BRAKE BUT REALIZED HE HAD NONE HE THEN ROLLED THROUGH THE INTERSECTION PAST A BUILDING AND DOWN  AN EMBANKMENT COLLIDING WITH THE RAILROAD TRACKS. ERNEST GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK AND REALIZED THE PUP TRAILER HAD TIPPED OVER AND THE REAR AXLE WAS ON FIRE AND OIL WAS COMING OUT OF A HOLE IN THE TANK CAUSE BY CRASH HE TRIED TO PUT THE FIRE OUT WITH HIS FIRE EXTINGUISHER BUT WAS NOT SUCCESSFUL. HE THEN CALLED 911, WHO THEN CALLED BURLINGTON NORTHERN THE OWNER OF THE RAILWAY, BY THE TIME THE FIRE TRUCK ARRIVED THE TRAILER WAS TOTALLY ON FIRE. THE FIREMAN CONTAINED THE BLAZE TO JUST THE TRAILER (TOTAL LOSS) AND THE TRUCK WAS NOT HARMED OTHER THEN COSMETIC DAMAGE. THE NATURAL TERRAIN CONTAINED THE SPILL TO 15 FOOT WIDE AREA DOWN TO 4 FOOT FOR ABOUT A 150 FEET LONG. THE TEMPERATURE WAS ABOUT -11 DEGREES THAT NIGHT AND THE GROUND FROZEN HELPED CONTAIN THE SPREAD OF THE OIL. THE MAJORITY OF THE OIL BURNT OFF. THE TERRAIN HELD THE REST UNTIL WE COULD DIG IT OUT. THE SITE HAS BEEN RECLAIMED. WE WERE NOT ABLE TO FIND THE CAUSE OF AIR LOSS OTHER THEN WINTER TEMPERATURE MUST HAVE HAD AN EFFECT ON THE AIRLINES BECAUSE THE TRAILER WAS A TOTAL LOSS. WE THINK THE FIRE STARTED  BY SPARKS IGNITING THE OIL THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE HOLE. ERNEST HAD NOT REPORTED ANY  BRAKING ISSUES AND HAD NO PROBLEMS EARLIER THAT DAY.
column169: WE HAVE DRIVERS PERIODICALLY ADD AIRLINE ANTIFREEZE TO THE AIR SYSTEM TO TRY AND STOP AIRLINES FROM FREEZING. WE HAVE TALKED EXTENSIVELY ABOUT THINKING A HEAD AND DEFENSIVE DRIVING FOR THE CONDITIONS. WE HAVE DRIVERS DOING PRETRIP INSPECTIONS IN HOPE OF FINDING ANY ISSUES BEFORE LEAVING THE YARD AND DOING WALK AROUNDS THROUGH OUT THE DAY. I FEEL LIKE THIS TRULY AN ACCIDENT BEYOND THE DRIVERS OR OUR CONTROL.

column168: Driver picked up trailer A94 from Polar Service Center in Tampa. He transported Trailer A94 empty to Airgas Davenport plant and loaded the trailer with 19.5% Aqua Ammonia, then began transporting to an intended destination in Brooksville, FL. He traveled on US-27 northbound in the left hand lane from Posner Blvd to Access Rd., then made a left on Access Rd and pulled into a restaurant. At approximately 1220hrs, as he was parking, a red Hyundai with 2 occupants pulled in front of him and stated his trailer was Leaking. The driver confirmed the complaint, seeing product Leaking from around the manhole cover and down the sides of the trailer. The passenger of the red car said he had some splash into the car and onto. his face and arm. The driver said she did not have any contact with'the product but could smell It. Vehicle was secured and the fire department took control of the scene. Preliminary investigation found that after receiving the trailer into service from the shop, the driver failed to properly close the dome lid, in order to make ready for product transport. It is estimated that the length of time of the release to be a few seconds to under a minute. The dome lid was cracked open and unsecured, leading to a splash condition through the cracked open lid during normal on-road maneuver.
column169: Immediate actions taken Included remedial/refresher training for receiving and preparing equipment from the shop to make ready for transport. Recommended changes include writing a separate SOP to handle accepting equipment from a shop and making ready for transport, including a checklist to ensure all valves, door, and lids are closed.

column17: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY
column168: ON 12/9/2019 AT 16:31, MTGX 7050 (ARGON, REFRIGERATED LIQUID) WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN A NORTHBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION AND SET OUT AT HEAVENER, OKLAHOMA FOR MITIGATION. A RAILROAD QUALIFIED RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS MOBILIZED TO INVESTIGATE AND MITIGATE THE LEAK.   RESPONDERS FOUND THE POINT OF RELEASE TO BE AN OPEN LEFT SIDE SAMPLE LINE VALVE (FULL OPEN POSITION), WITHOUT SECONDARY CLOSURE PLUG APPLIED. THE ORIGIN VALVE CABINET SEALS WERE ALL IN PLACE AND REMOVED THE FACILITATE RESPONSE. ADDITIONALLY, BUT WITHOUT RELEASE EVENT, RESPONSE CREW FOUND THE LEFT SIDE VAPOR VALVE SECONDARY CLOSURE PLUG NOT APPLIED AND THE RIGHT SIDE SAMPLE VALVE HANDLE NOT LOCKED AND ITS SECONDARY CLOSURE PLUG NOT APPLIED. THE RESPONSE CREW CLOSED THE LEFT SIDE SAMPLE LINE VALVE TO STOP THE RELEASE. THE SECONDARY CLOSURES WERE APPLIED AND VALVE HANDLES LOCKED ON BOTH THE LEFT AND RIGHT SAMPLE VALVES. THE VALVE CABINET WAS CLOSED AND RESEALED. ESTIMATED RELEASE IS 400 GALLONS. ONCE SECURED THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION TO DESTINATION.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD , THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THE PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: AS OUR DRIVER WAS EN ROUTE TO HIS DESTINATION HE CALLED THE PHONE # LISTED ON HIS PAPERWORK TO GET DIRECTIONS TO THE PLANT. THE PLANT OPERATOR THAT ANSWERED WAS FROM EULESS, TX. A SUBURB OF DALLAS FORT WORTH. THE DRIVER INFORMED THE OPERATOR WHO ANSWERED THE PHONE THAT HE WAS DELIVERING A LOAD OF SULFURIC ACID AND THE OPERATOR GAVE HIM DIRECTIONS. WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE GATE HE WAS MET BY THE OPERATOR WHO HE HAD SPOKEN WITH ON THE PHONE. OUR DRIVER THEN HANDED THE OPERATOR HIS BOL FOR INSPECTION. I ASKED OUR DRIVER IF HE TOLD THE OPERATOR WHAT PRODUCT HE WAS DELIVERING AND HE STATED THAT HE TOLD THE OPERATOR SEVERAL TIMES IT WAS SULFURIC ACID. AFTER REVIEWING THE PAPERWORK THE OPERATOR HOPPED ON HIS GOLF CART AND ESCORTED HIM BACK TO THE UNLOADING RACK. THE OPERATOR SHOWED OUR DRIVER WHERE TO HOOK UP AND INSTRUCTED HIM TO START OFFLOADING. THE OPERATOR THEN TOLD OUR DRIVER THAT HE WAS GOING HOME DUE TO SHIFT CHANGE AND ANOTHER OPERATOR WOULD BE AT THE RACK BY THE TIME THE TRAILER WAS OFFLOADED. WHEN THE NEW OPERATOR SHOWED UP HE NOTICED THE SMELL OF THE SULFURIC AND REALIZED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS UNLOADED INTO THE WRONG TANK. THE CUSTOMER'S TANK HE UNLOADED INTO HAD ABOUT 600 GALLONS OF FLOURIDE IN IT.
column169: SPOKE WITH THE DRIVER AND RE-ITERATED THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PRODUCT IS UNLOADED INTO THE CORRECT HOLDING TANK AND IF THERE IS ANY INDICATION OF ANY POSSIBLE ERROR NOT TO BEGIN THE UNLOADING PROCESS. THE ADDRESS ON THE BOL WAS IN DALLAS BUT THE PHONE NUMBER WAS TO ANOTHER LOCATION, SAME FACILITY NAME JUST A FEW MILES AWAY FROM WHERE HE WENT. WE HAVE NOT HEARD ANYMORE FROM THE FACILITY SINCE THE DELIVERY WAS MADE.

column168: DRIVER MADE A DELIVERY IN LADUE, MO AND WAS HEADED BACK TO THE OFFICE. IN MORNING RUSH-HOUR TRAFFIC, HEADED WESTBOUND ON INTERSTATE 40, EAST OFF BALLAS RD. THE DRIVER WAS SLOWING WITH TRAFFIC AND THEN CUT OFF BY BLUE HONDA CIVIC AND HAD TO BRAKE HARD. THEN THE DRIVER SENSED A STRONG BLEACH SMELL FROM THE TRUCK. HE EXITED THE HIGHWAY ONTO THE SHOULDER AND NOTICED THE HOSE HAD CRACKED AT THE BULK HEAD FITTING. HE USED THE PROPER PPE PROVIDED IN THE TRUCK AND USED THE SPILL RESPONSE KIT IN THE  TRUCK TO  CONTAIN THE MAJORITY OF THE LEAK IN THE TRUCK, AND USED A RUBBER PLUG TO STOP THE LEAK. HE CALLED INTO THE OFFICE, CONFIRMED THE TRUCK WAS NO LONGER LEAKING AND WAS TOLD TO HEAD BACK TO OFFICE WHERE WE HAD THE PROPER SPILL CONTAINMENT AND RESPONSE PROCEDURES IN PLACE FOR REMEDIATION.
column169: UPON INTERNAL REVIEW OF THE INCIDENT, THE CAUSE WAS AN OLDER HOSE THAT WAS BRITTLE DUE TO AGE AND THE FREEZING TEMPERATURE THAT MORNING. WE HAVE IMPLEMENTED A 6 MONTH PREVENTIVE MAINTENANCE PROCEDURE TO REPLACE THE HOSE COMING OFF THE TANK, AND THE BULK HEAD WILL BE REPLACED ANNUALLY. WE REVIEWED THE HOSE MATERIAL TO ENSURE THAT IT WAS THE PROPER HOSE FOR THE APPLICATION AND WE ARE USING DOUBLE STAINLESS CORROSION RESISTANT CLAMPS ON THE FITTING. WE WILL BE UPDATING OUR EQUIPMENT AS NEEDED WITH A SYSTEM THAT ELIMINATES THE NEED FOR A BULKHEAD ON THE TANK. THE PPE, AND AVAILABILITY  ALONG WITH THE SPILL RESPONSE AND CONTAINMENT EQUIPMENT AVAILABILITY WERE ALSO REVIEWED.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: EFFRAIN VALEZQUEZ (DALLAS TANK WAGON DRIVER) HAD A 5-10G NL SPILL WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY ON 12-19-19 AT 3PM. EFFRAIN STATED THAT HE WAS FILLING THE CUSTOMERS 1000 GALLON NL AST WHEN THE TANKS AUTOMATIC SHUT-OFF FAILED AND SPRAYED FUEL ON TOP OF THE TANK AND ONTO THE CONCRETE IN THE PARKING LOT. THE TANK GAGE WAS ONLY SHOWING 3/4 FULL. THERE WERE CARS PARKED ADJACENT TO THE TANK ON TOP OF THE STORM DRAIN. EFRAIN STATED HE DID NOT SEE THE DRAIN UNDER THE CAR AND DID NOT THINK IT MADE IT THAT FAR. HE STATED HE CLEANED OFF THE TANK AND THE CONCRETE ADJACENT TO THE TANK NEXT TO THE CAR. THE NEXT DAY THE CUSTOMER REPORTED A GASOLINE SMELL COMING UP FROM THE STORM DRAIN IN FRONT OF THEIR BUILDING. DARRELL PATTERSON WAS CONTACTED AND ARRIVED AT THE LOCATION AND FOUND THAT 2 OF THE DRAINS HAD A STRONG SMELL OF GASOLINE. TAS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS WITH THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY WAS CONTACTED AND AFTERWARDS APPROVED OF THE RESPONSE AND CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS (REPORT #2019-4553)
column169: -REPAIR CUSTOMERS AUTOMATIC SHUT OFF ON TANK (COMPLETED 1-10-20) -REPLACE CUSTOMERS TANK GAGE (COMPLETED 1-10-20)

column168: THE CMV WAS TURNING FROM GRASSY RD IN S HUNTINGTON TWP (RUFFSDALE), WESTMORELAND COUNTY PA INTO THE ENTRANCE OF THE CUSTOMER. AMERIGAS. THE DRIVER TURNED TOO SHARP ON THE SNOWY ROAD IN SLID INTO A DITCH ALONGSIDE THE ROADWAY AND ROLLED ONTO THE RIGHT SIDE. NO DAMAGE TO THE TANKER OR POWER UNIT OCCURRED. THE ROADWAY, NOT CONSIDERED A MAJOR ARTERY, WAS CLOSED FOR AN EXTENDED PERIOD OF TIME IN ORDER TO OFF LOAD THE PROPANE ONTO ANOTHER TANKER AND TO PROVIDE ADEQUATE SPACE FOR THE HEAVY DUTY TOW COMPANY TO UPRIGHT THE ROLLED TANKER. THE ONLY DAMAGE TO THE TRAILER WAS DAMAGE TO THE LANDING GEAR THAT WAS CAUSED BY THE TOW TRUCK RECOVERY OPERATIONS, NOT BY THE INITIAL ACCIDENT. THE TANKER WAS TOWED FROM THE SCENE TO THE LOW/RECOVERY YARD BY ORDER OF THE PA STATE POLICE , IN ORDER TO PERFORM A POST CRASH INSPECTION.  THE TRAILER WAS RELEASED FOLLOWING THE INSPECTION AND RETURNED TO THE C3 LOGISTICS FACILITY FOR REPAIRS TO THE LANDING GEAR.  NOTE: THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THERE WERE NO FATALITIES OR INJURIES. THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO ANY PART OF THE TANKER THAT MAY HAVE CAUSED A RELEASE OF PRODUCT (I.E. VALVES, HANDLES, PUMPS, ETC). THIS REPORT IS BEING SUBMITTED BEYOND THE REQUIRED 30 DAY LIMIT BECAUSE WE BELIEVED THAT WE WERE NOT REQUIRED TO FILE, AS PER 49 CFR 171.16 ET AL. ONCE WE WERE MADE AWARE OF THE REQUIREMENT, THIS REPORT WAS IMMEDIATELY COMPLETED.  NOTE: BLOCK 28: FORM WILL NOT ALLOW ENTRY OF MANUFACTURER DATE. YEAR 1988 (TRYS TO FILL IN 2088 YEAR)

column168: DRIVER NOTICED SMOKE EMANATING FROM REAR OF TANKER VEHICLE AND IMMEDIATELY EXITED HIGHWAY AND PARKED ON SHOULDER OF EXIT RAMP TO INVESTIGATE. UPON EXITING VEHICLE, DRIVER OBSERVED REAR INNER TIRE OF TANKER VEHICLE WAS ON FIRE AND THE FIRE WAS TOO LARGE TO EXTINGUISH WITH VEHICLE FIRE EXTINGUISHER. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED FIRE RESPONSE AGENCY BY CALLING 911. FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND EXTINGUISHED FIRE. HEAT FROM THE FIRE IMPINGED ON BOTTOM TANK FLANGE AND DAMAGING CORRESPONDING GASKET. DAMAGED GASKET RESULTED IN SMALL BUT CONSISTENT LEAK FROM BOTTOM FLANGE OUTLET.  DRIVER PLACED ABSORBENT PILLOWS TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE (BLEACH) AND PREVENT ENTRY INTO HIGHWAY DRAINAGE DITCH. CALTRANS WAS ONSITE AND PROVIDED ADDITIONAL DIRT TO ERECT A LARGER CONTAINMENT POND TO PREVENT SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE FROM ENTERING DRAINAGE DITCH.  WITH THE COORDINATION OF THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM AND THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL, HASA PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON SCENE AND IMMEDIATELY BEGAN THE TRANSFER OF REMAINING LIQUID FROM DAMAGED TANKER TO ANOTHER EMPTY TANKER. AS TANKER WAS BEING EMPTIED , A HAZARDOUS WASTE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, NATIONAL RESPONSE CORPORATION (NRC), UTILIZED A PUMP TRUCK TO RECOVER THE SPILLED BLEACH CONTAINED IN THE SMALL CONTAINMENT POND ERECTED TO MITIGATE FURTHER SPREAD OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL. NRC UTILIZED WATER TO SPRAY DOWN AREA OF CONTAINMENT POND TO ENSURE THAT ALL RESIDUAL BLEACH WAS RECOVERED AND AREA WAS CLEANED. ALL WASH WATER WAS PUMPED WITH SPILLED MATERIAL INTO INTERMEDIATE BULK CONTAINERS FOR FURTHER DISPOSAL. DURATION OF RELEASE WAS APPROXIMATELY 5.5 HOURS WITH APPROXIMATELY 900 GALLONS SPILLED AND RECOVERED WITH THE USE OF PUMP VEHICLE.
column169: PROVIDED REFRESHER TRAINING TO ALL DRIVERS TO ENSURE PROPER DAILY VEHICLE INSPECTIONS OF ALL EQUIPMENT IS BEING ACCOMPLISHED PROPERLY, SPECIFICALLY FOCUSED ON BRAKE AND TIRE RELATED SYSTEM COMPONENTS.  CONDUCTED A FLEET WIDE INSPECTION OF ALL OTHER TANKER FLEET EQUIPMENT TO ENSURE NO OTHER EQUIPMENT WAS SUBJECT TO SIMILAR INCIDENT.

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELING SOUTH BOUND INTERSTATE 5 IN ELK GROVE, CA., TO CUSTOMER OFF LOAD SITE. DRIVER EXITED INTERSTATE 5 AT ELK GROVE BLVD. OFF RAMP. WHILE NEGOTIATING LEFT HAND TURN, TRANSITIONING FROM OFF RAMP TO ELK GROVE BLVD., TRAILER OVERTURNED ONTO RIGHT SIDE. TRAILER SLID ONTO RIGHT SIDE. TRAILER SLID ON RIGHT SIDE OF CARGO TANK FOR APPROXIMATELY 100' ON ASPHALT ROADWAY. DUE TO IMPACT OF ROLL-OVER AND ROUGHNESS OF ROADWAY SURFACE, MID-SECTION RIGHT SIDE OF CARGO TANK WAS COMPROMISED FROM ROADWAY SURFACE. RIGHT SIDE OF CARGO TANK HAS SCRAPES AND GOUGES ALONG MID-SECTION FROM FRONT TO REAR, WITH REAR BULKHEAD SUSTAINING SIGNIFICANT DAMAGE ALONG WELDED SEAM. IMPACT CAUSED DEFORMATION OF WELDED SEAMS OF COMPARTMENT BULKHEADS, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO MOVE BETWEEN THE THREE VOIDS SEPARATING CONTAINMENT COMPARTMENTS AND INTO THE CENTER COMPARTMENT THAT HAD THE TEAR IN THE TANK SHELL ALLOWING PRODUCT LEAKAGE FROM CARGO TANK. WHILE TANK WAS RESTING ON ITS SIDE, PRODUCT WAS LEAKING. BY THE TIME A TOW TRUCK HAD UPRIGHTED THE CARGO TANK VEHICLE, 90% OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED OUT. DURATION OF LEAK WAS APPROXIMATELY 3-4 HOURS. THERE WERE NO MEANS AVAILABLE TO MITIGATE PRODUCT LEAKAGE DUE TO CONTAINMENT DAMAGE WHILE CARGO TANK WAS RESTING ON ITS SIDE.
column169: THIS INCIDENT HAS BEEN ATTRIBUTED TO FREEWAY EXIT SPEED WHILE NEGOTIATING LEFT HAND TURN WHEN TRANSITIONING FROM FREEWAY OFF RAMP ONTO SURFACE STREET. VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING AT 24MPH WHILE NEGOTIATING LEFT HAND TURN, WHEN IT WAS POSTED WITH A 10MPH SPEED SIGN. THIS INCIDENT WILL BE USED TO FURTHER TRAIN DRIVERS DURING DRIVER SAFETY MEETINGS ON SPEED AWARENESS AND LIQUID SURGE WHILE NEGOTIATING ROADWAY CURVES AND TURNS TO MINIMIZE A RECURRENCE OF THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT.  RECOMMENDATION IS FOR STATE DMV/FMCSA TO PROVIDE MORE SPECIFIC ENTRY LEVEL DRIVER TRAINING EDUCATION/TESTING FOR APPLICANTS APPLYING FOR A TANK VEHICLE ENDORSEMENT IN ORDER TO BRING A HIGHER SAFETY AWARENESS TOWARDS VEHICLES TRANSPORTING LIQUIDS.

column168: DEC 30, 2019 1 TOTE SULFURIC ACID WAS BEING UNLOADED OFF THE BACK OF A  SEMI TRAILER. DO TO UNEVEN PAVEMENT AND NOT LOWERING LOAD BEFORE MOVING HI-LOW, TOTE FELL OFF OF FORKS! TOTE LANDED ON ITS TOP MAKING 2 CORNERS ON SIDE OF TOTE TO CRACK RELEASING 90G OF SULFURIC INTO ROADWAY. FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED ALONG WITH HAZMAT AND CHEMICAL SUPPLIER. ABSORBENT SACKS WERE USED TO STOP THE FLOW TOWARDS STORM SEWER. SODA ASH WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE PH. HAZMAT CREATED 2 HOLES IN TOTE TO PUMP REMAINING SULFURIC OUT OF DAMAGED TOTE INTO A DIFFERENT TOTE THAT WAS PROVIDED. TOTE WAS TAKEN BACK TO SUPPLIER TO DETERMINE AMOUNT AMOUNT OF RELEASE.  ONCE DETERMINED NOTHING GOT INTO STORM SEWER AND PH NEUTRALIZED YOUNGS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED FOR CLEAN UP (DEC 30,19) ONCE CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED, I DECIDED NEXT DAY, DEC 31, 19 TO HAVE YOUNGS POWER WASH AND VACUUM UP REMAINING RESIDUE!
column169: WRITTEN INSTRUCTIONS RE-EVALUATED AND POSTED FOR ALL TO SEE! INTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN ATTACHED.  CONVERSATION WITH CHEMICAL SUPPLIER ON HOW AND WHERE LOADS ARE TO BE TAKEN OFF TRAILER. IT IS DIFFICULT FOR SEMI'S TO BACK INTO OUR LOADING DOCK!

Driver believed he had properly closed the bleeder valve on the Customer's side but it had not seated correctly, causing a spill of 100 gallons of Sodium Bisulfite into the containment area.
column169: "1.)   Valve was not properly closed and customer has not found any valve failure.   The cold weather could have been a factor,  but the fact remains that the driver did not ensure  that it was closed. 2.)   Driver signed off on SBS Loading Checklist that the valve was properly closed, when it was not. 3.)   Driver did not monitor the loading process correctly.  He should have checked both in & out of the building that everything was running properly and continued to monitor status during the entire loading process. 4.)  Complacency:  Assuming that everything was working properly instead of double checking. 5.)  Focus:  During loading and unloading procedures, the driver's attention should be fully on the successful completion of this primary responsibility. 6.)  Failure to follow procedure:   RIV-OPS-400 8.1.12:  ""Load/Fill 3/4"" Bleed Valve - Closed""  --Driver has received a documented verbal warning that future issues could lead to more serious disciplinary actions, up to and including termination. --December Safety Meetings next week will require attendance by all drivers and sign off on refresher training, including loading procedures, use of Loading Checklists as a tool, responsibility for monitoring entire loading process, complacency and being in a hurry, with Spill Prevention being primary goal.

Cesar checked the veeder reading and also checked the stick reading on the diesel tank.  Cesar then proceeded to deliver diesel at Quiktrip #4029. The spill was contained on the drop area, under the trailer and about a foot away from the left side of the trailer. Spring Branch Fire Department arrived and put down kitty litter to absorb the spill. A clean up service was contacted to clean up the remnants.

column168: Driver stated he hooked everything up, he had 40 ft of hose and the pump would not work.   He contacted his terminal and a mechanic was called. Mechanic found an air leak and a fitting had become loose.  They disconnected the hose and T9141R spilled out into the containment area.  Driver hooked it back up but no product was pumping.  They disconnected it once more and more  product spilled from the hose. Driver estimated the total amount to be around 20 gallons of product  spilled.  They waited awhile and re-connected, and the pump worked.  Unloading continued.
column169: When the pump was turned on, the blue hose blew off the pressure switch inside the engine  compartment. Pump should have been engaged before any valves on the trailer were turned open. Driver was retrained on how to use and maintain the pump.
